  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Barnes' Notes on the Bible",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Render \"and the children of Judah fought against Jerusalem, and took it, and smote it,\" etc. With regard to the capture of Jerusalem there is some obscurity. It is here said to have been taken, smitten with the edge of the sword, and burned, by the children of Judah. In ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Joshua 12:8",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Joshua 12:10",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " the Jebusite and the king of Jerusalem are enumerated among Joshua's conquests, but without any distinct mention of the capture of the city; and in the marginal reference we read that the Jebusites were not expelled from Jerusalem, but dwelt with the children of Judah (compare ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Judges 1:21",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). Further, we learn from ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Judges 19:10-12",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " that Jerusalem was wholly a Jebusite city in the lifetime of Phinehas ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Judges 20:28",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", and so it continued until the reign of David ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Samuel 5:6-9",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". The conclusion is that Jerusalem was only taken once, namely, at the time here described, and that this was in the lifetime of Joshua; but that the children of Judah did not occupy it in sufficient force to prevent the return of the Jebusites, who gradually recovered complete possession.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Set the city on fire - A phrase found only at Judges 20:48; 2 Kings 8:12, and Psalm 74:7. ",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "Set the city on fire - A phrase found only at ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
