      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " J, however, Hebron is captured by Caleb; it was a victory over the Anâkim, not over Canaanites in general; and such was undoubtedly the original version of the story. The editor here has altered the original narrative to fit his scheme of Judah’s victories; this has involved the removal of ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Jdg 1:20",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Jdg 1:20",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " from its proper place before ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Jdg 1:10",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Jdg 1:10",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". Fortunately the parallel passage in Joshua helps us to recover the original form of the text:",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Joshua 15:13-15",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ".  ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Jdg 1:20",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Jdg 1:10-11",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ".And unto Caleb the son of Jephunneh he gave [Hebron]†[22]. And Caleb drove out thence the three sons of Anak, Sheshai, and Ahiman, and Talmai, the children of Anak. And he went up thence against the inhabitants of Debir etc.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "[22] The words which intervene come from P.  And they gave Hebron unto Caleb, as Moses had spoken: and he drove out thence the three sons of Anak (20), Sheshai, and Ahiman, and Talmai (10b). And he went thence against the inhabitants of Debir etc. (11).",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "  ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Thus the whole of ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Jdg 1:10",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Jdg 1:10",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", except the names of the giants, is due to the editor. Arranging the text in this way we obtain a consistent narrative, a proper subject for the verb ‘and he went’ in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Jdg 1:11",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Jdg 1:11",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", and the introduction of Caleb at a point which explains how he came to be speaking in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Jdg 1:12",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Jdg 1:12",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ".",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Hebron",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "] The modern el-Ḥalîl (= ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "the friend",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), so called from its association with Abraham ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "the friend",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " of God, is the highest point in the Judaean Highlands, 3040 ft. above the sea. Its position made it the metropolis of the Negeb, which began a little to the south.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "now the name of Hebron beforetime was Kiriath-arba",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "] An archaeological gloss, cf. 11b. The ancient name of Hebron is frequently mentioned by P, e.g. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Genesis 23:2",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Joshua 15:54",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " etc.; in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Genesis 23:19",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Genesis 35:27",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " P it is given as Mamre. Kiriath-arba = lit. ‘city of four,’ i.e. Tetrapolis, perhaps because the city was divided into four quarters inhabited by different races; cf. Tripolis on the Phoenician coast, founded by Tyre, Sidon, and Aradus. The word ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "arba",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " is not a proper name, as a late Jewish tradition took it, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Joshua 14:15",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Joshua 15:13",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Joshua 21:11",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; in all three places the LXX has preserved the original reading ‘Kiriath-arba the metropolis of Anak.’ Burney in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Journ. Theol. Studies",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " 12:118 f. explains the name as ‘the city of (the god) Four’; he quotes Babyl. parallels for this usage; which, however, is questioned by some Assyriologists.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Sheshai, and Ahiman, and Talmai",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "] Either ‘the three sons of the Anak’ from ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Jdg 1:20",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Jdg 1:20",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " (cf. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Joshua 15:14",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") should precede; or we may place ‘the children of Anak’ after the names, following the LXX here and ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Joshua 15:14",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". The names may refer to families rather than to individuals; they look as if they were Aramaic. Sheshai (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Ezra 10:40",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") is connected by Sayce with the Shasu, i.e. ‘plunderers,’ or Bedouin of S. Canaan frequently alluded to on Egyptian monuments, though the forms are not philologically the same; cf. Sheshan in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Chronicles 2:31-35",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", a name belonging to this region. Ahiman ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Chronicles 9:17",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " probably = ‘brother of Měnî,’ the god of fortune, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Isaiah 65:11",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". Talmai is found in N. Arabia, in Nabataean inscriptions (C.I.S. ii. 321, 344, 348), and as the name of kings of Lihyan, an Arabian tribe (Müller, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Epigr. Denkmäler aus Arabien",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " nos. 4, 9, 25 from el-‘Öla). The three giants are mentioned in connexion with the visit of the spies, one of whom was Caleb, to Hebron ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Numbers 13:22",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Numbers 13:28",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " JE. The spies travelled northwards from Kadesh; and Caleb, when he attacked Hebron, most likely also advanced from the south. The two expeditions cannot have been separated by any long interval of time, according to the narrative of J.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Underlying the story there seems to be a dim recollection of the fact that the various clans which in time grew into the tribe of Judah, the Calebites, Kenites, Jerahmeelites, entered Canaan, not from the E. after crossing the Jordan, but from the S. by advancing from Kedesh.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Pulpit Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_sub_title",
        "text": "Verse 10.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " - ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "Hebron",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " See ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Numbers 13:22",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Joshua 14:13-15",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Joshua 15:13-19",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". Hebron was the burial-place of Abraham and Sarah (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Genesis 23:2",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", etc.; Genesis 25:9), of Isaac and Rebekah, and of Jacob and Leah (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Genesis 35:27-29",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Genesis 49:31",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Genesis 50:13",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), and the mosque, within whose massive walls the tombs of Abraham and the other four above mentioned are still preserved with the utmost reverence, is the most remarkable object in the modern city, which is called ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "El-Khalil",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " (the friend), after Abraham, the ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "friend of",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " God. A very interesting account of the Prince of Wales's visit to the Mosque of Hebron in 1862 is given in Dean Stanley s 'Sermons in the East.' David reigned in Hebron seven years and six mouths before he transferred the seat of power to Jerusalem (see ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Samuel 2:1",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", etc.; 2 Samuel 5:1-5). Judges 1:10",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Keil and Delitzsch Biblical Commentary on the Old Testament",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "After the conquest of Jerusalem, the children of Judah (together with the Simeonites, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Judges 1:3",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") went down to their own possessions, to make war upon the Canaanites in the mountains, the Negeb, and the shephelah (see at ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Joshua 15:48",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Joshua 21:33",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), and to exterminate them. They first of all conquered Hebron and Debir upon the mountains (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Judges 1:10-15",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), as has already been related in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Joshua 15:14-19",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " (see the commentary on this passage). The forms עלּית and תּחתּית (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Judges 1:15",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), instead of עלּיּות and תּחתּיּות (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Joshua 15:19",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), are in the singular, and are construed with the plural form of the feminine גּלּות, because this is used in the sense of the singular, \"a spring\" (see Ewald, 318, a.). ",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  }
]